SEEDS AND
 FERTILIZERS

            Introduction of
           seeds and fertilizers

SEEDS: Seeds are the starting point for growing plants. They contain the genetic material necessary for a plant to develop. When you plant seeds, they germinate and grow into seedlings, which eventually become mature plants.

FERTILIZERS: Fertilizer, natural or artificial substance containing the chemical elements that improve growth and productiveness of plants. Fertilizers enhance the natural fertility of the soil or replace chemical elements taken from the soil by previous crops.

Introduction of seeds

SEED:  A seed is a basic part of any plant.

It is the product of the ripened ovule after fertilization, and it contains an embryo and a food reserve enclosed in a protective outer covering called a seed coat. When planted, a seed can develop into a new plant.

           

           Types of seeds

                                                                                     

  • Conventionally seeds are classified into

  • Endospermic/Albuminous: endospermic seed: dominant endosperm dependent immature embryo is present

  • Non endospermic/ Exalbuminous: The seeds which do not contain endosperm are called as exalbuminous or non endospermic seeds.

Structure and development of seeds

  • Seed: ripened ovule containing embryo.

  •  Developed after the fertilization of female gamete by male gamete

  • It is developed in the embryo sac of the ovule in ovary of a flower

Characteristics of Seeds

  • Size of seed varies from just like(orchid seeds-wt 20.33micro gram)to large(double coconut-wt16kg)

  •   Large seed produce large seedling.

  •   Seed size has a vital role in determining seed vigour.

Importance of seeds

  • Propagation of new generation of species(called as "NATURAL WEALTH" THAT SUSTAINS PLANTS & ANIMAL LIFE)

  •      Used directly as food

  •      For extraction of oil

  •      For extraction of malt

  •      Used as medicines

Introduction of fertilizers

Fertilizer: A fertilizer or fertilizer is any material of natural or synthetic origin that is applied to soil or to plant tissues to supply plant nutrients. 

                                        (or)

A fertilizer is any material of natural or synthetic origin that is applied to soils or to plant tissues to supply one or more plant nutrients essential to the growth of plants.

              Basic forms of fertilizers

  • Granular- designed to be scratched into the soil and water soluble.

  •  Powdered- designed to be dissolved in water for liquid feeding to soil and foliage.

  •  Liquid- usually a concentrated form to be mixed with water.

Classicifications of fertilizer types

  • Straight fertilizers  :These are those which supply only one primary plant nutrient(N,P&K).

  • E.g. Urea, Ammonium chloride and potassium sulphate.

Complex fertilizers: These are contain 2 or 3 primary plant nutrients of which two primary nutrients are in chemical combination.

  • Usually produced in granular form.

  • Mixed fertilizers:

These are physical mixtures of straight fertilizers.

They contain 3 or more primary plant nutrients.
